commit_list.message:
Update marker display on zoom as well as pan

The app was using the 'dragend' event on the map to listen for
changes that should prompt the display of markers, but that event
only triggers when the map is panned. Changing to the 'idle' event
ensures that the display is updated on both zoom and pan instead
of requiring users to slightly pan the map after zooming to get
new data.

This has the side effect of making the initial markers display
immediately upon loading the page, rather than waiting for the user
to pan, as the idle event occurs when the map is initially loaded.

commit_list.message:
Fix placement of overmap specials with city size 0

Update the selection of overmap specials for placement to exclude those
which require a city size > 0 when city size is 0.

Prior to this change, overmap specials would generally fail to be placed
in a world created with city size 0.

This is because when considering specials for placement, the game:
* did not exclude those that would be impossible to place (requiring city size > 0)
* had a limited number of tries for a given sector of the map to attempt placement
* would exhaust the tries attempting to place impossible specials

The result would be an overmap generally devoid of specials. This also
had the side effect of creating several additional overmaps as the game
searched for and created adjacent overmaps to hold mandatory specials
that could never actually be added.

Fixes #22827

Update tools/vehicleDef.py to export multiple in save and include items

The script previously required that you know the map file containing
the vehicle you wanted to export, as well as the name of the vehicle.
The script will now allow you to specify a save folder and an optional
vehicle name. It will then scan all maps in the save for vehicles
(optionally filtering to those with a matching name) and process them.

Additionally, the script will extract the items in the vehicle parts
and construct an appropriate item section for a vehicle template to be
edited as necessary by the designer.

Each item is listed independently with a 100% spawn chance--adjusting
spawn chances, collapsing items into arrays, and referencing item groups
is an exercise left to the designer.

Adjust FRAG effect explosion distance factor

The FRAG effect was creating explosions with a 1.0 distance factor
which would then trigger an error in the bounds checking of the
`game::explosion` method (`"called game::explosion with factor >= 1.0 (infinite size)"`).

Based on the comment associated with the FRAG effect
(`// Same as a standard thrown frag grenade.`)
the distance factor was adjusted down to 0.8, which is the default value
used when explosions don't define a distance factor, which the frag
grenade does not.

Fixes #24630

Update vehicleDef.py to produce better vehicle templates

This script previously made the assumption that the order in which parts
were listed in the save file was valid for a vehicle template, but that
assumption is easily invalidated if the user is using Hammerspace to
build the vehicle.

To cut down on the amount of manual work required to get a good vehicle
template, I updated this script to sort the vehicle frame parts such
that they are listed in a connected order (e.g. each frame is adjacent
to another existing frame).

I also updated the script to use OrderedDict to ensure that the json
keys retained their original order, which keeps the id, type, name, and
part x, y, and type all in the expected order.

commit_list.message:
Fix game not saving selected display for startup

The game calls string_format when the getting the value for an
int_map option field (which "DISPLAY" is), passing in the format
string for the option. However, the int_map add function did not
set a format string, and so the value specified in the options
never made it into the serialized options, and thus the default
value was used on startup.

Update check ensuring in-game before refreshing UI after resize

Previous check was asserting that the character's name was not
empty as a check that the world was loaded and ready for the
refresh. However, in the character creation screen, it is possible
to have a character name and not have a loaded world. Resizing the
window would then lead to a crash.

This updates that check to instead verify that the user's ID has
been initialized.

commit_list.message:
Propagate overmap special placement reporting to caller

Changing the way overmap specials are passed during placement such
that a copy of the available specials are passed to adjacent overmaps
fixed the issue with optional specials being placed, but changed the
way the placement appeared to be reported to the caller--only placements
on that overmap were reported.

This updates the logic so that a callee's placements are also taken into
account when reporting to the caller, so externally it's effectively the
same behavior as prior to the copy change.

commit_list.message:
Fix overmap special exhaustion when placing mandatory specials

Fixes the issue where attempting to place mandatory specials can
result in no optional specials being placed on any overmap except
the final overmap being created.

If mandatory specials can't be placed on the current overmap,
we would then create a new adjacent overmap and attempt to place
the mandatory specials there. This continues until we either place
all the mandatory specials or hit our limits. Then, we'd proceed
from that final overmap backwards to our original, placing optional
specials.

Because placed specials are removed from the candidate list,
the final overmap would get generally get all of the specials placed
and every other overmap that was created in between the start and final
would have no specials to place, resulting in empty overmaps.

This change simply sends a copy of the remaining specials into the
method that creates the additional overmaps, so that when the specials
are removed from the list of options on the final and every intervening
overmap, all previous overmaps can still attempt to place the optional
specials.

commit_list.message:
Update marker display on zoom as well as pan

The app was using the 'dragend' event on the map to listen for
changes that should prompt the display of markers, but that event
only triggers when the map is panned. Changing to the 'idle' event
ensures that the display is updated on both zoom and pan instead
of requiring users to slightly pan the map after zooming to get
new data.

This has the side effect of making the initial markers display
immediately upon loading the page, rather than waiting for the user
to pan, as the idle event occurs when the map is initially loaded.

commit_list.message: Add Linux Tiles build to travis
Add Windows Tiles build to travis
Change MXE keyserver per instructions at http://pkg.mxe.cc/
Call pip and apt-* with travis_retry

Fix inventory compare input handling

Update game_menus::inv::compare to use input_context for processing
inputs, bringing the available keybindings more in line with the
rest of the application and ensuring that unintended inputs
(e.g. moving the mouse) don't close the comparison window.
Fix iteration when erasing overmap specials (#25306)

Propagate overmap special placement reporting to caller

Changing the way overmap specials are passed during placement such
that a copy of the available specials are passed to adjacent overmaps
fixed the issue with optional specials being placed, but changed the
way the placement appeared to be reported to the caller--only placements
on that overmap were reported.

This updates the logic so that a callee's placements are also taken into
account when reporting to the caller, so externally it's effectively the
same behavior as prior to the copy change.
Add test for mapgen optional specials at origin

Fix overmap special exhaustion when placing mandatory specials

Fixes the issue where attempting to place mandatory specials can
result in no optional specials being placed on any overmap except
the final overmap being created.

If mandatory specials can't be placed on the current overmap,
we would then create a new adjacent overmap and attempt to place
the mandatory specials there. This continues until we either place
all the mandatory specials or hit our limits. Then, we'd proceed
from that final overmap backwards to our original, placing optional
specials.

Because placed specials are removed from the candidate list,
the final overmap would get generally get all of the specials placed
and every other overmap that was created in between the start and final
would have no specials to place, resulting in empty overmaps.

This change simply sends a copy of the remaining specials into the
method that creates the additional overmaps, so that when the specials
are removed from the list of options on the final and every intervening
overmap, all previous overmaps can still attempt to place the optional
specials.

Update check ensuring in-game before refreshing UI after resize

Previous check was asserting that the character's name was not
empty as a check that the world was loaded and ready for the
refresh. However, in the character creation screen, it is possible
to have a character name and not have a loaded world. Resizing the
window would then lead to a crash.

This updates that check to instead verify that the user's ID has
been initialized.

Fix game not saving selected display for startup

The game calls string_format when the getting the value for an
int_map option field (which "DISPLAY" is), passing in the format
string for the option. However, the int_map add function did not
set a format string, and so the value specified in the options
never made it into the serialized options, and thus the default
value was used on startup.

Fix placement of overmap specials with city size 0

Update the selection of overmap specials for placement to exclude those
which require a city size > 0 when city size is 0.

Prior to this change, overmap specials would generally fail to be placed
in a world created with city size 0.

This is because when considering specials for placement, the game:
* did not exclude those that would be impossible to place (requiring city size > 0)
* had a limited number of tries for a given sector of the map to attempt placement
* would exhaust the tries attempting to place impossible specials

The result would be an overmap generally devoid of specials. This also
had the side effect of creating several additional overmaps as the game
searched for and created adjacent overmaps to hold mandatory specials
that could never actually be added.

Fixes #22827

Update tools/vehicleDef.py to export multiple in save and include items

The script previously required that you know the map file containing
the vehicle you wanted to export, as well as the name of the vehicle.
The script will now allow you to specify a save folder and an optional
vehicle name. It will then scan all maps in the save for vehicles
(optionally filtering to those with a matching name) and process them.

Additionally, the script will extract the items in the vehicle parts
and construct an appropriate item section for a vehicle template to be
edited as necessary by the designer.

Each item is listed independently with a 100% spawn chance--adjusting
spawn chances, collapsing items into arrays, and referencing item groups
is an exercise left to the designer.

Adjust FRAG effect explosion distance factor

The FRAG effect was creating explosions with a 1.0 distance factor
which would then trigger an error in the bounds checking of the
`game::explosion` method (`"called game::explosion with factor >= 1.0 (infinite size)"`).

Based on the comment associated with the FRAG effect
(`// Same as a standard thrown frag grenade.`)
the distance factor was adjusted down to 0.8, which is the default value
used when explosions don't define a distance factor, which the frag
grenade does not.

Fixes #24630

Update vehicleDef.py to produce better vehicle templates

This script previously made the assumption that the order in which parts
were listed in the save file was valid for a vehicle template, but that
assumption is easily invalidated if the user is using Hammerspace to
build the vehicle.

To cut down on the amount of manual work required to get a good vehicle
template, I updated this script to sort the vehicle frame parts such
that they are listed in a connected order (e.g. each frame is adjacent
to another existing frame).

I also updated the script to use OrderedDict to ensure that the json
keys retained their original order, which keeps the id, type, name, and
part x, y, and type all in the expected order.
Pull lookup values out to common
Rename CNB type files for consistency
Add a mock client that pushes data to a remote
Update decoder process to print type 1 messages
Add Position Report Class A message (type 1)
Rename bittwiddling functions and fix shifting bug
Fix call stack error with math.min/max
Reduce log verbosity and better error messages
Add ability to filter which messages print debug

Return raw rate of turn for 128, 127, -127

Rate of turn values of 128, 127, and -127 have special meaning,
and I was previously encoding them as math.NaN() and math.Inf, but
this causes problems when trying to marshal the CNB types to Json,
as those aren't allowed. Since someone would want to interpret these
values into the associated strings anyway for display purposes (e.g.
showing "turning right at more than 5deg/30s" for 127) I don't see
much value in keeping what I had, and if anything it's more confusing
for interpretation later.
Refactor decoder cmd to extract decoding and package accumulation
Include timestamp in parsing for historical data sources
Use Set and Map for lookups
Fix bug where packets with errors were accumulated
Get rid of png export from main app
